# TESS Program G05054

Title: Detecting And Characterizing Companions To Warm Jupiters

PI: Mireles, Ismael - University Of New Mexico

Type: SMALL

Summary: TESS has led to the discovery of hundreds of new planetary systems as well as new planets in previously known planet systems. Of particular note, are systems with known warm to temperate gas giant planets that have been found to have transiting companions. We propose to obtain TESS photometry of stars that are known to host gas giants with periods ranging from 10 to 200 days in order to search for additional companions. Additional interior and exterior companions detected in these systems will further inform planet formation and evolution models while non-detections will help place further constraints on their occurrence. Included in the sample are known planet systems that will be first observed by TESS in Cycle 5.
